# EC2 — Elastic Compute Cloud

EC2 is AWS's virtual machine service. It is the foundation of most AWS architectures — even if you eventually move to containers, you are almost always running on EC2 nodes underneath.

---

## Core Concepts

**AMI (Amazon Machine Image)** — The template for your instance. Think of it as a snapshot of an OS + software. AWS provides Amazon Linux, Ubuntu, RHEL, Windows. You can also create your own.

**Instance Type** — Defines CPU, memory, and network. Format: `family.size` (e.g. `t3.medium`, `c6i.xlarge`, `r7g.2xlarge`)

| Family | Use Case |
|--------|----------|
| t3/t4g | General purpose, burstable (dev/test, small workloads) |
| m6i/m7i | General purpose, steady (web servers, app servers) |
| c6i/c7i | Compute optimized (CI runners, batch processing) |
| r6i/r7i | Memory optimized (databases, caches) |
| p/g | GPU (ML training, inference) |

**Key Pair** — SSH public/private key pair. AWS stores the public key, you keep the private key. Without it you cannot SSH in.

**Security Group** — A virtual firewall. Controls inbound and outbound traffic at the instance level. Stateful — if you allow inbound on port 80, the response traffic is automatically allowed outbound.

**EBS (Elastic Block Store)** — Persistent disk attached to your instance. Survives instance stops/restarts (unlike instance store which is ephemeral).

