## EBS Volumes

```bash
# List volumes
aws ec2 describe-volumes \
  --query 'Volumes[*].[VolumeId,Size,State,Attachments[0].InstanceId]' \
  --output table

# Create and attach an extra volume
aws ec2 create-volume \
  --size 50 \
  --volume-type gp3 \
  --availability-zone ap-south-1a

aws ec2 attach-volume \
  --volume-id vol-xxxxxxxx \
  --instance-id i-xxxxxxxx \
  --device /dev/xvdf

# On the instance — format and mount it
sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/xvdf
sudo mkdir /data
sudo mount /dev/xvdf /data
# Add to /etc/fstab for persistence across reboots
echo "/dev/xvdf /data ext4 defaults,nofail 0 2" | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
```

**Volume types:**
- `gp3` — general purpose SSD, baseline 3000 IOPS. Default choice.
- `io2` — provisioned IOPS SSD, for databases needing consistent high IOPS.
- `st1` — throughput optimized HDD, for big sequential reads (logs, data lakes).

